                "psalm_proverbs": "<h2>1. Loyalty to God in our plans</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>Our first loyalty is to God. His favour rests on those who are &lsquo;God-loyal&rsquo; (v.19, MSG).</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The book of Proverbs is full of practical wisdom. It encourages you, for example, to be discerning about what you believe: &lsquo;The gullible believe anything they&rsquo;re told; the prudent sift and weigh every word&rsquo; (v.15, MSG). Ultimately wisdom is about how you relate to God: &lsquo;The wise fear the Lord and shun evil&rsquo; (v.16).</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&lsquo;Fear of the Lord&rsquo; is an attitude of healthy respect and loyalty. It means involving him in all your plans. We need to be very careful about the plans we make &ndash; that they are for good and not for evil. Eventually, even &lsquo;the wicked will respect God-<em>loyal </em>people&rsquo; (v.19, MSG).</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&lsquo;But those who plan what is good find <em>love </em>and <em>faithfulness</em>&rsquo; (v.22b). The word for &lsquo;find&rsquo; is sometimes translated &lsquo;show&rsquo;. Both are true. Those who plan what is good not only <em>find </em>love and faithfulness, they <em>show </em>love and faithfulness as well. This is at the heart of loyalty &ndash; to show love and faithfulness. This is contrasted with those who selfishly plot evil and go astray.</p>\r\n\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p>Lord, help me to be wise and God-loyal in my plans. Show me more ways to be kind to the needy. May we, as a community of God-loyal people, plan what is good and find love and faithfulness.</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n",
                "new_testament": "<h2>2. Loyalty to Jesus in our words</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>As the apostles went out and preached the good news they performed <em>many </em>miraculous signs and wonders among the people. &lsquo;More and more men and women believed in the Lord and were added to their number&rsquo; (v.14). As a result, &lsquo;Crowds gathered&hellip; bringing their sick&hellip; <em>all </em>of them were healed&rsquo; (vv.15&ndash;16).</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Sadly, their success led to &lsquo;jealousy&rsquo; from religious leaders (v.17). Once again we see how envy is such a temptation for those of us who are seen as religious. In their jealousy they arrested the apostles and put them in jail (v.18). But once again God performed a miracle. He sent an angel of the Lord to open the doors of the jail and bring them out.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>With huge courage they obeyed the command to &lsquo;Go, stand in the temple courts&hellip; and tell the people the full message of this new life&rsquo; (v.20).</p>\r\n\r\n<p>When they were caught doing exactly what they had been arrested for doing in the first place, they were re-arrested and brought before the Sanhedrin to be questioned by the high priest who said to them, &lsquo;We gave you strict orders not to teach in this name&hellip; Yet you have filled Jerusalem with your teaching and are determined to make us guilty of this man&rsquo;s blood&rsquo; (v.28).</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Peter and the other apostles were loyal to God and to their calling. They replied, &lsquo;We must obey God rather than human beings!&rsquo; (v.29).</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Jesus said, &lsquo;Give to Caesar what is Caesar&rsquo;s,&nbsp;and to God what is God&rsquo;s&rsquo; (Matthew 22:21). In saying this, he defined the limits of loyalty to the authority of human beings. When it conflicts with loyalty to God, God takes precedence. Out of loyalty to God, they continued preaching the gospel &ndash; even when they were on trial.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The brief sermon (it takes only three verses &ndash; Acts 5:30&ndash;32) is all about Jesus. They preach about the cross, resurrection and the exaltation of Jesus. They proclaimed Jesus as Prince and Saviour. The talk includes a description of the way of salvation: repentance and forgiveness of sins.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In addition they managed to include the whole Trinity. God the Father: &lsquo;The God of our ancestors (v.30), God the Son: &lsquo;Jesus&rsquo; (v.30) and God &lsquo;the Holy Spirit&rsquo; (v.32). This sermon produces such fury that, like the South Korean missionaries, they faced the threat of death.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>However, in the providence of God, there was a wise man on the Sanhedrin, a Pharisee named Gamaliel, who pointed out to his fellow members (by giving examples from recent history) that &lsquo;if [the apostles&rsquo;] purpose or activity is of human origin, it will fail. But if it is from God, you will not be able to stop these men; you will only find yourselves fighting against God&rsquo; (vv.38&ndash;39).</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Although his speech persuaded them, nevertheless the apostles were flogged and &lsquo;ordered&hellip; not to speak in the name of Jesus&rsquo; (v.40).</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Once again, with extraordinary courage and loyalty to God and their calling, &lsquo;The apostles left the Sanhedrin, rejoicing because they had been counted worthy of suffering disgrace for the Name. Day after day, in the temple courts and from house to house, they never stopped teaching and proclaiming<em> the good news that Jesus is the Christ</em>&rsquo; (vv.41&ndash;42).</p>\r\n\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p>Lord, may we be inspired by the example of the apostles and those like the South Korean missionaries who followed in their footsteps. Help us to demonstrate loyalty to you regardless of the circumstances and opposition around us. May we never stop teaching and proclaiming the good news that Jesus is the Christ.</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n",
                "old_testament": "<h2>3. Loyalty to each other in our hearts</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>Loyalty is such an attractive characteristic in a person. Disloyalty is subversive and betrays trust. Disloyalty can undermine the leadership in a church, business or even a nation.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In David&rsquo;s case, disloyalty came from his own son. This must have been so painful for him. David loved Absalom; &lsquo;the king&rsquo;s heart longed for Absalom&rsquo; (14:1). God speaks to David through the wise woman from Tekoa. As a result David says, &lsquo;Go, bring back the young man Absalom&rsquo; (v.21). When he returned &lsquo;the king kissed Absalom&rsquo; (v.33). David gave him another opportunity to be a loyal son.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Tragically, David&rsquo;s love and loyalty to Absalom were not returned. We see here a powerful description of how disloyalty works.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>There are always opportunities for disloyalty. In any situation &ndash; whether for example in the government, workplace or the church &ndash; there are bound to be those who complain (15:2). If you are a loyal person you will help to deal with these complaints and attempt to diffuse them.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It has been said, &lsquo;Loyalty means I am down with you whether you are wrong or right. But I will tell you when you are wrong and help you get it right.&rsquo;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Absalom failed the loyalty test. He would say to the complainers,&nbsp;<span style=\"line-height: 1.6em;\">&lsquo;&ldquo;Look, you&rsquo;ve got a strong case; but the king isn&rsquo;t going to listen to you.&rdquo; Then he&rsquo;d say, &ldquo;Why doesn&rsquo;t someone make me a judge for this country? Anybody with a case could bring it to me and I&rsquo;d settle things fair and square.&rdquo;&rsquo; (vv.3&ndash;4, MSG).</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Of course, this is absolute nonsense. But it is easy to make promises of this kind. The disloyal person says, &lsquo;If only I were in charge everything would be so much better.&rsquo; In this way Absalom &lsquo;<em>stole the hearts of the people of Israel</em>&rsquo; (v.6). Disloyalty begins in our hearts and in our thinking. So does loyalty. Guard your heart and your thinking and do not allow your heart to be stolen.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Those who are feeling discontented in any situation always look for a rallying point. They look for someone among the leadership team whom they can rally around. If the entire leadership team remains faithful, the discontents will be unsuccessful. However, here they found a rallying point around Absalom and &lsquo;the conspiracy gained strength, and Absalom&rsquo;s following kept on increasing&rsquo; (v.12).</p>\r\n\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p>Lord, help us to stay loyal to our leaders &ndash; to our national leaders and governments, parents, church leaders and bosses. Lord, guard our hearts, keep us loyal to you and to one another. May loyalty, love and faithfulness always be characteristics of our community.</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n",
                "pippa_adds": "<p><strong>2 Samuel 14:1&ndash;15:12</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Being beautiful on the outside doesn&rsquo;t make you beautiful on the inside. Absalom had a perfect appearance, but what was going on inside was quite different. People spend hours going to gyms, hairdressers, doing make-up, clothes shopping and working on their outward appearance. What really matters is what&rsquo;s going on inside. We all need to work harder on our inner beauty.&nbsp;</p>\r\n",
